		<div id="listing-items">
			
							
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Smart-Start-first-steps-to-managing-intellectual-property-in-a-new-business" title="Smart Start: first steps to managing intellectual property in a new business" alt="link">Smart Start: first steps to managing intellectual property in a new business</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>IP Australia</i>. Smart Start is an introduction to basic intellectual property (IP) concepts for anyone who is starting or buying a business. Starting a business can be daunting, and IP issues are often misunderstood or overlooked in this important phase. The last three chapters in this online guide contain handy facts and contacts for further information, including an IP glossary and a contacts directory for further help and advice with your business and IP.</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Smart-Start-first-steps-to-managing-intellectual-property-in-a-new-business">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/WIPO-UNEP-study-on-the-role-of-intellectual-property-rights-in-the-sharing-of-benefits-arising-from-the-use-of-biological-resources-and-associated-traditional-knowledge" title="WIPO-UNEP study on the role of intellectual property rights in the sharing of benefits arising from the use of biological resources and associated traditional knowledge" alt="link">WIPO-UNEP study on the role of intellectual property rights in the sharing of benefits arising from the use of biological resources and associated traditional knowledge</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>Anil K. Gupta, WIPO-UNEP, November 2004.</i> This study identifies and explores the role of IPRs in the sharing of benefits arising from the use of biological resources and associated traditional knowledge. Agreement on how IP derived from access is used and how the benefits are shared is an important part of the exercise of prior informed consent, and an important practical way of ensuring a true partnership between custodian and user of the genetic resource. Three case studies, from Mali, Nigeria and India, highlight lessons learned that will be useful for policymakers and stakeholders in showing how the effective protection of IPRs can support the conservation and sustainable use of biodiversity, as well as the equitable sharing of benefits arising from the use of biological and genetic resources.</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/WIPO-UNEP-study-on-the-role-of-intellectual-property-rights-in-the-sharing-of-benefits-arising-from-the-use-of-biological-resources-and-associated-traditional-knowledge">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Dodging-patent-perils-in-collaborations" title="Dodging patent perils in collaborations" alt="link">Dodging patent perils in collaborations</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>The Scientist, vol.18(21), November 2004</i>. Research collaborations often form the bedrock of truly great science. Scientific alliances can also help businesses commercialize their basic research or reveal the next blockbuster drug. In recent years, economic and competitive pressures have encouraged research collaborations between universities and industry, and between small biotech companies and Big Pharma. While these associations frequently prove to be beneficial for all parties, research collaborations can sometimes trap the unwary, creating legal entanglements and endangering intellectual property rights. Recent US court decisions on such cases, as well as pending legislation, may affect research relationships in 2005 and beyond. The challenge is to build research partnerships while protecting intellectual property rights.</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Dodging-patent-perils-in-collaborations">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Progress-achievements-and-constraints-for-plant-biotechnology-in-developing-countries" title="Progress, achievements and constraints for plant biotechnology in developing countries" alt="link">Progress, achievements and constraints for plant biotechnology in developing countries</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>AgBioTech, Special issue, vol. 7(1&amp;2), 2004</i>. A series of reports focusing on technologies that have increased (or promise to increase) agricultural production in developing countries. Some of the writers describe the challenges that must be overcome before genetically enhanced crops will be commercialized in underdeveloped countries. Many of these challenges are the consequence of lack of scientific preparedness; others are the result of misinformation and misinterpretation, leading to confusion and misunderstanding among potential consumers. It is clear that the work of scientists does not end with discovery or with product development. Instead, it continues through the training of the students and researchers who will become leaders of research teams in developing countries.</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Progress-achievements-and-constraints-for-plant-biotechnology-in-developing-countries">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Science-and-Poverty-An-Interdisciplinary-Assessment-of-the-Impact-of-Agricultural-Research" title="Science and Poverty: An Interdisciplinary Assessment of the Impact of Agricultural Research" alt="link">Science and Poverty: An Interdisciplinary Assessment of the Impact of Agricultural Research</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>R. Meinzen-Dick et al., IFPRI, October 2004</i>. Agricultural research has greatly increased the yields of important staple food crops, yet many people in rural areas in developing countries still live in abject poverty. Therefore, policymakers, donors, and researchers are refocusing their priorities away from simply producing more food to making sure that agricultural research benefits the poor. This report synthesizes the lessons learned from seven case studies that show that measures of the direct impacts of new technologies on incomes and yields do not tell the whole story. Social, cultural and economic factors all influence whether the poor adopt or receive direct and indirect benefits from new technologies. Therefore, it is crucial that impact assessments include a mix of disciplines and methods, and that researchers do not only focus on poverty-reducing impacts that are easy to measure.</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Science-and-Poverty-An-Interdisciplinary-Assessment-of-the-Impact-of-Agricultural-Research">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Saving-Seeds-The-Economics-of-Conserving-Crop-Genetic-Resources-Ex-Situ-in-the-Future-Harvest-Centres-of-CGIAR" title="Saving Seeds: The Economics of Conserving Crop Genetic Resources Ex Situ in the Future Harvest Centres of CGIAR" alt="link">Saving Seeds: The Economics of Conserving Crop Genetic Resources Ex Situ in the Future Harvest Centres of CGIAR</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>Ed. B. Koo et al., CABI Publishing, October 2004</i>. The conservation of genetic resources is vital to the maintenance of biodiversity and to the worlds ability to feed its growing population. There are now more than 1000 genebanks worldwide involved in the ex situ storage of particular classes of crops. Since the 1970s, the 11 genebanks maintained by the CGIAR centres have become pivotal to the global conservation effort. However, key policy and management issues - usually with economic dimensions - have largely been overlooked. This book reports on a series of detailed economic studies, led by IFPRI, and discusses their wider implications.</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Saving-Seeds-The-Economics-of-Conserving-Crop-Genetic-Resources-Ex-Situ-in-the-Future-Harvest-Centres-of-CGIAR">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Environmental-Risk-Assessment-of-Genetically-Modified-Organisms-Volume-1-A-Case-Study-of-Bt-Maize-in-Kenya" title="Environmental Risk Assessment of Genetically Modified Organisms, Volume 1: A Case Study of Bt Maize in Kenya" alt="link">Environmental Risk Assessment of Genetically Modified Organisms, Volume 1: A Case Study of Bt Maize in Kenya</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>Ed. A Hilbeck and D. Andow, CABI Publishing, October 2004</i>. It is widely recognised that comprehensive, transparent scientific methods are needed for the pre-release testing and post-release monitoring of transgenic plants, and that the regulatory and scientific capacity for conducting these types of assessments needs to be strengthened. In response, the International Organization for Biological Control launched a project to develop biosafety testing guidelines for transgenic plants. This book is one of the first outputs from the project. Using the case of Bt maize in Kenya, the book details generic approaches to the evaluation of environmental impacts of transgenic plants, provides general risk assessment guidelines, and demonstrates the need for case-by-case analysis. Although focused on Kenya and Bt maize, the findings and recommendations are relevant to a multitude of nations and GM crops.</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Environmental-Risk-Assessment-of-Genetically-Modified-Organisms-Volume-1-A-Case-Study-of-Bt-Maize-in-Kenya">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Innovation-and-Its-Discontents-How-our-broken-patent-system-is-endangering-innovation-and-progress-and-what-to-do-about-it" title="Innovation and Its Discontents: How our broken patent system is endangering innovation and progress, and what to do about it" alt="link">Innovation and Its Discontents: How our broken patent system is endangering innovation and progress, and what to do about it</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>A.B. Jaffe and J. Lerner, Princeton University Press, September 2004</i>. The US patent system has become sand rather than lubricant in the wheels of progress. The book tells how recent changes in patenting ? an institutional process that was created to nurture innovation ? have wreaked havoc on innovators, businesses, and economic productivity. The authors show how legal changes initiated in the 1980s converted the system from a stimulator of innovation to a creator of litigation and uncertainty that threatens the innovation process itself.</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Innovation-and-Its-Discontents-How-our-broken-patent-system-is-endangering-innovation-and-progress-and-what-to-do-about-it">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Smallholder-African-Agriculture-Progress-and-Problems-in-Confronting-Hunger-and-Poverty" title="Smallholder African Agriculture: Progress and Problems in Confronting Hunger and Poverty" alt="link">Smallholder African Agriculture: Progress and Problems in Confronting Hunger and Poverty</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>D. Resnick, IFPRI Discussion Paper No. 9, 2004</i>. This paper examines recent trends in poverty, malnutrition, and growth to delineate where the challenges are the greatest and to highlight cases of success. The performance of smallholder agriculture receives particular attention due to its role in sustaining the livelihoods of a majority of Africa's poor. In recent years, the importance of smallholder agriculture has been recognized, demonstrated by the pledges of African governments and the donor community to engage in interventions for generating agricultural growth.</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Smallholder-African-Agriculture-Progress-and-Problems-in-Confronting-Hunger-and-Poverty">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Conflict-Social-Capital-and-Managing-Natural-Resources-A-West-African-Case-Study" title="Conflict, Social Capital and Managing Natural Resources: A West African Case Study" alt="link">Conflict, Social Capital and Managing Natural Resources: A West African Case Study</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>Ed. K.M. Moore, CABI Publishing, 2004</i>. This book is the product of a six-year multi-disciplinary research programme in sustainable agriculture and natural resource management. It describes the transition of the conflict-ridden agricultural and pastoral systems of arid and semi-arid regions of West Africa to more intensified agricultural and animal husbandry systems. The research investigates technological options and decision tools and explores a replicable methodology for building social capital within a rural community in the Niger Delta. The chapters recount the efforts of researchers and development agents to identify new approaches for sustainable development and the experiences of the local population.</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Conflict-Social-Capital-and-Managing-Natural-Resources-A-West-African-Case-Study">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Regulating-the-Liabilities-of-Agricultural-Biotechnology" title="Regulating the Liabilities of Agricultural Biotechnology" alt="link">Regulating the Liabilities of Agricultural Biotechnology</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>S. Smyth et al., CABI Publishing, 2004</i>. This book examines how government, industry and society interact to reach a level of regulation that is deemed satisfactory for agricultural biotechnology. It considers issues of risk and trust surrounding genetically modified plants for the production of food and pharmaceuticals. It describes how regulations have been produced to manage, or in some cases ignore, the risks from GM products.</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Regulating-the-Liabilities-of-Agricultural-Biotechnology">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Trade-and-Development-Report-2004-Policy-Coherence-Development-Strategies-and-Integration-Into-The-World-Economy" title="Trade and Development Report 2004: Policy Coherence, Development Strategies and Integration Into The World Economy" alt="link">Trade and Development Report 2004: Policy Coherence, Development Strategies and Integration Into The World Economy</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>UNCTAD, September 2004</i>. Global economic recovery is underway. But will it be sustained, and will it benefit all countries? There are considerable downside risks stemming from oil prices and exchange rates. Moreover, both the sources and incidence of growth are unequally distributed around the globe.</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Trade-and-Development-Report-2004-Policy-Coherence-Development-Strategies-and-Integration-Into-The-World-Economy">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Democratising-Biotechnology" title="Democratising Biotechnology" alt="link">Democratising Biotechnology</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>Institute of Development Studies (IDS), Sussex, UK</i>. This series of papers from the IDS programme of research into agricultural biotechnology, globalisation and development examines a key dilemma surrounding agricultural biotechnology: are the poor in the developing world likely to gain the most from biotechnological innovation, or, alternatively, will they be the most badly affected by the introduction of genetically modified crops? A central theme to the research is the need to democratise biotechnology in order to avoid some of the worst case scenarios, and to ensure that imagined food and farming futures really are 'pro-poor'.</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Democratising-Biotechnology">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/African-Asian-agriculture-against-AIDS" title="African-Asian agriculture against AIDS" alt="link">African-Asian agriculture against AIDS</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>FAO/UNDP, 2004</i>. HIV/AIDS is creating a crisis in the rural areas of the countries most severely affected by this disease. The agricultural sector has a fundamental role to play in mitigating the impact of the pandemic. This paper reports on the Consultation on Agriculture, Development and HIV-vulnerability reduction held in Bangkok in 2002. Concrete interventions, based on the expertise and comparative advantage of the agricultural sector in the area of medicinal herbs, indigenous plants and labour-saving technologies, have been identified as fruitful lines of intervention. The paper calls for the immediate implementation of such interventions by governmental organisations and NGOs responsible for agriculture and rural development.</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/African-Asian-agriculture-against-AIDS">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Plant-Diversity-Sustainable-Rural-Livelihoods-and-the-HIV-AIDS-Crisis" title="Plant Diversity, Sustainable Rural Livelihoods and the HIV/AIDS Crisis" alt="link">Plant Diversity, Sustainable Rural Livelihoods and the HIV/AIDS Crisis</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>J.A. Gari, UNDP, June 2004</i>. A large proportion of small farmers in the South face food insecurity, live in marginal environments and are highly vulnerable to the impact of HIV/AIDS. The responses of the agricultural sector are often conceived of outside the community context and neglect the local resource base, both natural and cultural. Increased attention should be given to the potential of local plant diversity (agrobiodiversity) to combat malnutrition, agricultural constraints and the HIV/AIDS crisis. This paper outlines an agrobiodiversity strategy with the following components: traditional, neglected and under-utilised crops; agricultural diversification; home gardens; wild food plants; medicinal plants; and community seed systems. </p>
							<p><span class="date">22/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Plant-Diversity-Sustainable-Rural-Livelihoods-and-the-HIV-AIDS-Crisis">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Report-of-the-Expert-Consultation-on-Environmental-Effects-of-Genetically-Modified-Crops" title="Report of the Expert Consultation on Environmental Effects of Genetically Modified Crops" alt="link">Report of the Expert Consultation on Environmental Effects of Genetically Modified Crops</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>FAO, May 2004</i>. The cultivation of genetically modified (GM) crops is changing agriculturale practices in a number of developed and developing countries. The area of GM crops planted worldwide continues to increase. As agriculture is intrinsically linked to the environment, in June 2003 the FAO invited 16 technical experts to assess the current understanding of the effects of GM crops on ecosystems, identify gaps and priorities and indicate the role of the FAO in this context. The experts discussed the environmental effects of major GM crops, including those used for pest management, drought and salinity tolerance, both above and below ground. The discussions led to the recognition of effects that need to be considered during introduction of GM crops within specific agro-ecosystems.</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Report-of-the-Expert-Consultation-on-Environmental-Effects-of-Genetically-Modified-Crops">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Least-Developed-Countries-Report-2004" title="Least Developed Countries Report 2004" alt="link">Least Developed Countries Report 2004</a></h2>

	
					<p>  <i>UNCTAD, May 2004</i>. This report assesses the relationship between international trade and poverty within the LDCs, and identifies national and international policies that can make trade a more effective mechanism for poverty reduction in these countries. </p>
							<p><span class="date">22/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Least-Developed-Countries-Report-2004">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Twenty-Third-FAO-Regional-Conference-for-Africa" title="Twenty-Third FAO Regional Conference for Africa" alt="link">Twenty-Third FAO Regional Conference for Africa</a></h2>

	
					<p>  <i>Johannesburg, South Africa, 1-5 March 2004</i>. <a href="http://www.fao.org/docrep/meeting/007/j1604e.htm" target="_blank">Implementation of the Comprehensive Africa Agriculture Development Programme (CAADP) of NEPAD ? Progress Review</a>.  </p>
							<p><span class="date">22/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Twenty-Third-FAO-Regional-Conference-for-Africa">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Public-private-partnerships-in-agricultural-research-An-analysis-of-challenges-facing-industry-and-the-CGIAR" title="Public-private partnerships in agricultural research: An analysis of challenges facing industry and the CGIAR" alt="link">Public-private partnerships in agricultural research: An analysis of challenges facing industry and the CGIAR</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>D.J. Spielman and K. von Grebmer, EPTD Discussion Paper No. 113, IFPRI, January 2004</i>. Public?private partnerships offer potentially important opportunities for pro-poor agricultural research in developing countries. Yet we see few examples of successful public?private partnerships, and fewer examples where such collaborations have contributed to food security, poverty reduction and economic growth. This study assesses the opportunities for, and challenges to, creating and sustaining partnerships between the agricultural research centres of the CGIAR and multinational, research-based agribusiness companies. </p>
							<p><span class="date">22/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Public-private-partnerships-in-agricultural-research-An-analysis-of-challenges-facing-industry-and-the-CGIAR">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Science-Technology-and-Innovation-for-the-21st-Century" title="Science, Technology and Innovation for the 21st Century" alt="link">Science, Technology and Innovation for the 21st Century</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>OECD Committee for Scientific and Technological Policy, 9 February 2004</i>. At a High-level Forum on ?Key Challenges for Science and Innovation Policy?, ministers highlighted the benefits that society can derive from advances in science and technology. They focused on three issues that are high on the science and innovation policy agendas of OECD countries: 1) promotion of stronger relationships between science and innovation systems; 2) ensuring sustained development of human resources in science and technology; and 3) enhanced international cooperation in science and technology.</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Science-Technology-and-Innovation-for-the-21st-Century">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
											</div> 	
	<br class="cl" />
<p>

